        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A research fellow is utilizing PCR techniques for the detection of a specific gene mutation in a sample. She wants to amplify a small amount of DNA to a quantity sufficient for analysis. Which of the following best describes the key component necessary for the PCR process to successfully amplify the DNA?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3203082",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34969,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Taq polymerase enzyme.</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>PCR </strong>(Polymerase Chain Reaction) is a <strong>technique used to amplify small segments of DNA</strong>. The <strong>key component </strong>for this process is the <strong>Taq polymerase enzyme</strong>. This <strong>enzyme is thermostable</strong>, meaning it can <strong>withstand the high temperatures </strong>used in <strong>PCR to denature the DNA strands</strong>. <strong>Taq polymerase </strong>is responsible for <strong>synthesizing new strands of DNA </strong>by adding <strong>nucleotides to a primer annealed </strong>to the <strong>template DNA</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Reverse transcriptase enzyme </strong>is used in <strong>reverse transcription PCR </strong>(RT-PCR) for <strong>converting RNA into DNA</strong>, not in standard PCR.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>DNA ligase enzyme </strong>is used for <strong>joining DNA fragments together</strong>, which is not the primary function in the PCR process.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Restriction endonuclease enzyme cuts DNA </strong>at <strong>specific sequences </strong>and is not involved in the amplification process of PCR.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Taq polymerase enzyme </strong>as the <strong>key component </strong>in the <strong>Polymerase Chain Reaction </strong>(PCR) <strong>process </strong>is crucial for <strong>amplifying specific DNA segments</strong>. This <strong>enzyme&#39;s thermostable nature</strong>, which <strong>allows it to withstand high temperatures </strong>used in <strong>PCR for denaturing DNA strands</strong>, is essential for the synthesis of new DNA strands.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Apurva Sastry Essentials of Microbiology, pg 46 /4e</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
