        {
          "id": 16231,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Increased specificity due to two rounds of amplification with different primer sets</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 16232,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Decreased time for amplification</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 16233,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Reduced need for template DNA</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 16234,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Elimination of the need for thermal cycling</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A molecular biologist is employing Nested PCR for the detection of a low-abundance pathogen in a clinical sample. This technique involves two sets of primers and two successive PCR reactions. What is the primary advantage of using Nested PCR compared to traditional PCR methods?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6595957",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34970,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Increased specificity due to two rounds of amplification with different primer sets.&nbsp;</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Nested PCR </strong>is a <strong>modification of the standard PCR technique </strong>that <strong>increases the specificity of DNA amplification</strong>. By <strong>using two sets of primers in two successive PCR reactions</strong>, <strong>Nested PCR allows </strong>for the <strong>amplification of a specific target sequence </strong>with <strong>greater precision</strong>. The <strong>first set of primers amplifies a broad region of DNA</strong>, and the <strong>second set</strong>, which is <strong>internal to the first amplified sequence</strong>, further refines the specificity, reducing the likelihood of non-specific amplification.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Decreased time for amplification </strong>is <strong>incorrect</strong>, as Nested PCR typically takes longer due to the two rounds of PCR.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Reduced need for template DNA </strong>is <strong>not a primary advantage of Nested PCR</strong>. While it can <strong>amplify small amounts of DNA</strong>, the technique&#39;s focus is on specificity, not reducing the amount of template DNA required.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Elimination of the need for thermal cycling is incorrect</strong>. Nested PCR, like traditional PCR, still <strong>requires thermal cycling for DNA denaturation, </strong>primer annealing, and extension.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Nested PCR enhances </strong>the <strong>specificity of DNA amplification </strong>by <strong>using two sets of primers in two successive PCR reactions</strong>, thereby <strong>reducing the likelihood of non-specific amplification</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Apurva Sastry Essentials of Microbiology, pg 46 /4e</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
