          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">To protect bacteria from the eukaryotic immune system</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">What is the primary function of the CRISPR system in bacteria?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6239371",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34965,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) To enable bacteria to resist viral infections through sequence-specific DNA cleavage.</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>CRISPR systems </strong>(Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) - The <strong>primary function </strong>of the CRISPR system in <strong>bacteria is to provide adaptive immunity against phage infections </strong>through the <strong>sequence-specific cleavage of foreign DNA.&nbsp; CRISPR&#39;s role </strong>is specifically <strong>defensive</strong>, <strong>targeting and neutralizing invading phage DNA </strong>rather than <strong>assimilating or expressing it</strong>. This system is also distinct in its purpose from protecting bacteria against the eukaryotic immune system, as its primary focus is on phage defense.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong>&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">To <strong>facilitate horizontal gene transfer between bacterial cells</strong>: Incorrect. CRISPR is <strong>not directly involved </strong>in horizontal gene transfer.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>To allow the incorporation of viral DNA into the bacterial genome</strong>: Incorrect. While CRISPR <strong>does involve the incorporation of spacer sequences</strong>, its function is defense, not integration for expression.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>To protect bacteria from the eukaryotic immune system</strong>: Incorrect. <strong>CRISPR is a bacterial defense against viruses</strong>, not a protection mechanism against the eukaryotic immune system.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>CRISPR systems </strong>(Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats)&nbsp; <strong>provide bacteria with adaptive immunity against phages </strong>by <strong>targeting and cleaving foreign DNA sequences.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif; font-size:12pt; text-decoration-line:underline\">Ref:</span>&nbsp;</strong><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Aptos&quot;,sans-serif\"><a href=\"https://www.genome.gov/genetics-glossary/CRISPR\" style=\"color:#467886; text-decoration:underline\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">https://www.genome.gov/genetics-glossary/CRISPR</span></span></strong></a></span></span></p>",
